      <hedline>
        <hl1>Double-Deckers, Death and Shame</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Werner Winkler letter, commenting on May 27 article, says double-decker tour buses give visitors a disgraceful first impression of New York</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Besides traffic and pollution problems, double-decker buses (editorial, May 27) can provide visitors with a disgraceful first impression of New York.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Besides traffic and pollution problems, double-decker buses (editorial, May 27) can provide visitors with a disgraceful first impression of New York.</p>
        <p>Last fall, we took our friends from London on a day tour. This involved three buses, each with some defects. On one, the rear door jammed open, allowing the exhaust to enter during transit. On another, half of the street-level windows were covered with ads. Poor amplification and engine noise blocked out most of the commentary by the tour guides. And because of traffic or lack of buses, the wait time between pickups was very long, so we were able to make only two brief stops.</p>
        <p>Ever the diplomats, our guests enjoyed the day and reminded us of the school buses we took 60 years ago. Of course, they were in better condition then.</p>
        <p>WERNER WINKLER  Morristown, N.J., May 27, 2000</p>
      </block>
